        "references": [
            "System heterogeneity settings. We follow the settings in (Horváth et al., 2021) and divide the available M𝑀M clients into 5 uniform clusters, i.e. each cluster has M/5𝑀5M/5 clients. Clients from the same cluster have identical system configurations (e.g. CPU, memory, storage). To match the five tiers of clients, we deploy five Microsoft Azure VMs from different resource groups, as listed in Table 1. All VMs use the operating system Ubuntu Server 20.04 LTS - x64 Gen 2, and the processor Intel Xeon E5-2673 v3 @2.40GHz. Each VM holds at most M/5𝑀5M/5 parallel processes, with each process representing one client. Specifically, VM1 holds clients 1∼M/5similar-to1𝑀51\\sim M/5, VM2 holds clients M/5+1∼2​M/5similar-to𝑀512𝑀5M/5+1\\sim 2M/5, etc.",
            "Energy consumption. We use energy consumption to evaluate the performance of FLrce in terms of computation efficiency (Yang et al., 2020; Imteaj et al., 2022). For a GPU-free VM, the power consumption can be calculated by the overheads of CPU. Compared with CPU, other elements (e.g. memory, storage) consume much less energy and can be ignored (Bergman, 2021; Fan et al., 2007). For a Microsoft Azure VM, the energy consumption is the product of the number of vCPU cores, utilization, wall clock running time and the thermal design power (TDP, see Table 1) (Bergman, 2021; int, [n. d.]). Accordingly, in every round, we record the average CPU utilization and training time of each VM to calculate the required energy. For example, if VM2 runs 10 seconds with an average CPU utilization of 50%, the expected energy consumption is 2×10×0.5×110=11002100.511011002\\times 10\\times 0.5\\times 110=1100W."
        ]
