        "footnotes": "",
        "references": [
            "The experiment outcomes demonstrate that existing efficient FL frameworks might slow down the speed of collaborative learning. Oppositely, by means of the client selection and early stopping strategy, FLrce is able to accelerate the learning process and complete it in advance. For example, from Table 2, for HAR, the validation accuracy of the baselines are 86.6%∼91.0%similar-topercent86.6percent91.086.6\\%\\sim 91.0\\% after 500 rounds. As a comparison, FLrce stops at round 275 with an accuracy of 87.5%percent87.587.5\\%. Similarly, for ID, the baselines spend 200 rounds to reach an accuracy of 53.9%∼62.7%similar-topercent53.9percent62.753.9\\%\\sim 62.7\\%, while FLrce merely requires 59 rounds to get 59.3%percent59.359.3\\%. For NLP, FLrce ends up with a negative perplexity of -3.4, which is slightly worse than the best result (-2.2, OD). However, FLrce only spends 53 rounds for training while the baselines spend 100.",
            "For complex tasks like image classification, dropout might even degrade the accuracy, as the server cannot extract sufficient learning information from the resource-constrained devices whose data are important to train an accurate global model. As shown in Table 2, for IC, the best validation accuracy among the baselines is 65.7% (PD), which is achieved after 500 rounds. Comparatively, FLrce can reach an accuracy of 73.8% using only 101 rounds.",
            "It is worth noting that the performance of Feddrop on IC and NLP is catastrophic. From Figure 10 and Table 2, we can see that Feddrop almost learns nothing and ends up with an accuracy/negative perplexity of 2.9%/-37.0. There are three possible reasons. 1. Feddrop is developed on the assumption that the drop rate is fixed across all clients. Therefore, it might not support adaptive drop rates on heterogeneous clients (Horváth et al., 2021). 2. Feddrop drops units in a random manner. However, not all units in a model contribute equally, training or communicating the unimportant units might significantly degrade the learning efficiency (Li et al., 2022, 2021). 3. When the resource-constrained devices store the data that are important to collaborative learning, training a miniature sub-model on these devices will prohibit the server from acquiring the necessary information to train a solid deep learning model, like CNN or RNN.",
            "Due to the existence of the ES mechanism, FLrce is able to reduce overall energy consumption. As Figure 11 shows, FLrce consumes the least energy for all the tasks except for ID. For ID, the performance of FLrce is second only to PyramidFL. However, PyramidFL does not maintain accuracy, as the validation accuracy of PyramidFL is only 53.9% for ID (Table 2), making the computation efficiency worthless.",
            "To investigate whether the ES mechanism will cause undesirable accuracy loss, we compare the final accuracy/negative perplexity of FLrce and FLrce without early stopping (FLrce w/o ES). The only difference between FLrce and FLrce w/o ES is that the latter ignores the ES criterion and keeps training until reaching the maximum global iteration. Note that the relationship-based client selection strategy still applies. As Table 3 shows, the ES mechanism does not cause too much loss of accuracy/negative perplexity. On the worst case, the ES mechanism degrades the final accuracy by 8.8% (IC). However, the ES mechanism reduces almost 80% training rounds (101 vs. 500). Besides, FLrce still outperforms the baselines for IC even with the accuracy deduction (see Table 2)."
        ]
